import{_ as a}from"./index-6a78bd73.js";import{o as e,f as t,q as i}from"./vue-b065e30f.js";import"./vue-router-7a1c4c9d.js";const d={class:"research-page"};const o=a({name:"ResearchPage"},[["render",function(a,o,s,r,c,n){return e(),t("div",d,[...o[0]||(o[0]=[i('<section class="content-section" data-v-8856cefa><h2 class="section-title" data-v-8856cefa>Introduction</h2><div class="section-content" data-v-8856cefa><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Medical radiation diagnostics practitioners are routinely exposed to low-dose ionizing radiation while performing X-ray imaging, computed tomography (CT), and digital subtraction angiography (DSA), and while working in nuclear medicine settings where gamma rays or beta particles may be present.  Although occupational doses are regulated and typically far below those causing acute injury, chronic exposure can still produce cumulative biological effects. Because hematopoietic tissues are among the most radiosensitive systems, even subtle damage may be detectable in peripheral blood measurements long before clinical disease becomes apparent. </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Chromosomal aberrations (CAs) in peripheral blood lymphocytes are a sensitive biomarker for ionizing radiation effects and are widely used in biological dosimetry. Aberrations such as dicentric chromosomes, centric rings, and acentric fragments reflect DNA double-strand breaks and misrepaired chromosome ends, and can be scored in metaphase spreads using standardized criteria.  In China, CA testing has been incorporated into occupational health surveillance standards for radiation workers, supporting both baseline assessment and ongoing monitoring.  However, the prevalence of CAs and their associated risk factors can vary by workplace, task type, and duration of exposure, making institution-level evidence valuable for targeted prevention. </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Against this background, the present study evaluates chromosomal aberrations in peripheral blood immune cells among medical radiation diagnostics practitioners undergoing occupational medical examinations. The analysis includes 1,125 workers from a tertiary hospital in Guangdong Province, China, evaluated between January 2023 and December 2024.  By comparing hematologic indicators and CA outcomes across demographic and exposure-related subgroups, and by applying logistic regression modeling, the study aims to clarify whether age and cumulative exposure time are associated with increased chromosomal aberration risk, thereby providing practical evidence to strengthen occupational health surveillance and radiation protection strategies in medical settings. Such evidence is especially relevant for prioritizing long-tenured staff for intensified follow-up and preventive interventions. </p></div></section><section class="content-section section-gray" data-v-8856cefa><h2 class="section-title" data-v-8856cefa>Research Method</h2><div class="section-content" data-v-8856cefa><h3 class="subsection-title" data-v-8856cefa>Study design and participants：</h3><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> The study enrolled 1,125 medical radiation diagnostics practitioners who completed occupational health examinations at a tertiary hospital in Guangdong Province, China, between January 1, 2023 and December 31, 2024.  Participants were categorized into subgroups by gender, age, and length of service (radiation exposure duration) to support comparative analysis across demographic and exposure strata.  Recorded variables included age, gender, job category, and duration of occupational radiation exposure, along with routine hematology indices. </p><h3 class="subsection-title" data-v-8856cefa>Chromosomal aberration assay：</h3><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> For each participant, 0.5 mL of peripheral venous blood was collected and cultured in 5 mL RPMI-1640 medium. Cultures were treated with colchicine (0.04 μg/mL) and incubated at (37.0 ± 0.5) °C for 52 hours, followed by hypotonic treatment, fixation, and slide preparation.  Images were captured using a GSL120 automated chromosome scanning system (Leica, Germany), and 100–150 metaphase spreads per sample were selected for scoring with CytoVision software.  Aberration types were counted and recorded, with independent verification by two technicians. Positivity criteria followed GBZ248-2014: a dicentric chromosome plus centric ring rate &gt;1%, or an acentric fragment rate &gt;3% </p><h3 class="subsection-title" data-v-8856cefa>Routine blood testing：</h3><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> An additional 1 no. healthy whole blood sample were collected and preserved on a filter(ab (C2C9510 heterology analysis). Normalized region steps where level with cover A(a G,( 1.2TC; cytogenetic international and immunology(c.c.)) sample level. Detection protocols are well-study protocol for system with Lenzxson measure. Detection result determination was carefully documented. </p><p class="section-table-title" data-v-8856cefa>Table 1 Comparison of baseline characteristics between the two groups</p><table class="data-table" data-v-8856cefa><thead data-v-8856cefa><tr data-v-8856cefa><th data-v-8856cefa>Variables</th><th data-v-8856cefa>Non-aberration group (n=1060)</th><th data-v-8856cefa>Aberration group (n=65)</th><th data-v-8856cefa>t/χ²</th><th data-v-8856cefa>P</th></tr></thead><tbody data-v-8856cefa><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>Age</td><td data-v-8856cefa>33.17±10.420</td><td data-v-8856cefa>37.97±13.627</td><td data-v-8856cefa>-2.787</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.007</td></tr><tr class="group-header" data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>Gender</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label indent" data-v-8856cefa>Male</td><td data-v-8856cefa>638</td><td data-v-8856cefa>46</td><td data-v-8856cefa>2.877</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.090</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label indent" data-v-8856cefa>Female</td><td data-v-8856cefa>422</td><td data-v-8856cefa>19</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>Radiation exposure duration (years)</td><td data-v-8856cefa>6.85±8.137</td><td data-v-8856cefa>10.43±10.322</td><td data-v-8856cefa>-2.747</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.008</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>White blood cell count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>(5.95±1.467)×10⁹/L</td><td data-v-8856cefa>(5.99±1.611)×10⁹/L</td><td class="highlight" data-v-8856cefa>-1.174</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.862</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>Platelet count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>(261.47±44.17)×10⁹/L</td><td data-v-8856cefa>(256.68±51.192)×10⁹/L</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.691</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.691</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>Absolute lymphocyte count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>(1.94±0.501)×10⁹/L</td><td data-v-8856cefa>(1.96±0.553)×10⁹/L</td><td data-v-8856cefa>-0.328</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.743</td></tr><tr class="group-header1" data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td></tr></tbody></table><p class="section-table-title" data-v-8856cefa>Figure 1. Chromosomal aberrations in lymphocytes</p><div class="change-container" data-v-8856cefa><div class="table-container" data-v-8856cefa><img src="/research/1.webp" alt="Table 1: Comparison of baseline characteristics between the two cohort" class="table-image" data-v-8856cefa><p class="image-caption" data-v-8856cefa>A: normal chromosome</p></div><div class="figure-container" data-v-8856cefa><img src="/research/2.webp" alt="Figure 2: Chromosomal alterations in lymphocytes" class="figure-image" data-v-8856cefa><p class="image-caption" data-v-8856cefa>B: dicentric chromosome</p></div><div class="table-container" data-v-8856cefa><img src="/research/3.webp" alt="Table 2: Univariate logistic regression analyses" class="table-image" data-v-8856cefa><p class="image-caption" data-v-8856cefa> C: tricentric chromosome</p></div><div class="table-container" data-v-8856cefa><img src="/research/4.webp" alt="Table 3: Multivariate logistic regression analyses" class="table-image" data-v-8856cefa><p class="image-caption" data-v-8856cefa>D: ring chromosome</p></div></div><h3 class="subsection-title" data-v-8856cefa>Statistical analysis</h3><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Continuous variables were summarized as mean ± standard deviation, and categorical variables as counts and percentages. Differences in prevalence across groups were examined using chi-square testing. Logistic regression (univariate and multivariate) evaluated associations between chromosomal aberrations and candidate predictors (age, gender, exposure duration, and blood indices), using SPSS 23.0 with statistical significance set at p&lt;0.05. </p><p class="section-table-title" data-v-8856cefa>Table 2 Univariate logistic regression analysis</p><table class="data-table" data-v-8856cefa><thead data-v-8856cefa><tr data-v-8856cefa><th data-v-8856cefa>Variables</th><th data-v-8856cefa>β</th><th data-v-8856cefa>OR</th><th data-v-8856cefa>95%C.I.</th><th data-v-8856cefa>P-value</th></tr></thead><tbody data-v-8856cefa><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Age</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.035</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.036</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.015-1.056</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.001</td></tr><tr class="group-header" data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Gender</td><td data-v-8856cefa>-0.471</td><td data-v-8856cefa>–</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.361-1.081</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.092</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Male</td><td data-v-8856cefa>–</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1</td><td data-v-8856cefa>–</td><td data-v-8856cefa>–</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Female</td><td data-v-8856cefa>–</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.624</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td><td data-v-8856cefa>—</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Radiation exposure duration (years)</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.042</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.043</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.017-1.070</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.001</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>White blood cell count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.015</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.015</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.858-1.201</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.862</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Platelet count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>-0.002</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.998</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.994-1.003</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.489</td></tr><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>Absolute lymphocyte count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.082</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.086</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.665-1.773</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.743</td></tr><tr class="group-header1" data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label bold" data-v-8856cefa>count</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.082</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.086</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.665-1.773</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.743</td></tr></tbody></table><p class="section-table-title" data-v-8856cefa>Table 3 Multivariate logistic regression analysis</p><table class="data-table" style="margin-bottom:0;" data-v-8856cefa><thead data-v-8856cefa><tr data-v-8856cefa><th data-v-8856cefa>Variables</th><th data-v-8856cefa>β</th><th data-v-8856cefa>OR</th><th data-v-8856cefa>95%C.I.</th><th data-v-8856cefa>P-value</th></tr></thead><tbody data-v-8856cefa><tr data-v-8856cefa><td class="row-label" data-v-8856cefa>Radiation exposure duration (years)</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.039</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.039</td><td data-v-8856cefa>1.013-1.067</td><td data-v-8856cefa>0.003</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class="content-section" data-v-8856cefa><h2 class="section-title" data-v-8856cefa>Discussion</h2><div class="section-content" data-v-8856cefa><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Across 1,125 examined radiation workers, 65 individuals (5.8%) met the criteria for chromosomal aberrations, whereas 1,060 (94.2%) were classified as non-aberrant.  Baseline comparisons showed that the aberration group was older and had longer occupational exposure duration than the non-aberration group (age: 37.97±13.63 vs 33.17±10.42 years; exposure duration: 10.43±10.32 vs 6.85±8.14 years), suggesting a cumulative effect.  In contrast, routine hematology indicators (white blood cell count, platelet count, and absolute lymphocyte count) did not differ significantly between groups in this dataset. </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Representative metaphase images illustrated typical aberration morphologies—including dicentric chromosomes, tricentric chromosomes, and ring chromosomes—used for scoring.  A dicentric chromosome results from breaks in two chromosomes with subsequent joining of centromere-containing segments, while a centric ring usually forms after two breaks in a single chromosome and end-to-end rejoining; acentric fragments may be lost during division. </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Regression analyses supported exposure duration and age as key predictors of chromosomal aberrations. In univariate models, both age (OR=1.036) and exposure duration (OR=1.043) were significant, whereas gender and blood indices were not.  After adjustment for gender and hematologic covariates, exposure duration remained an independent risk factor: each additional year of occupational radiation exposure corresponded to a 3.9% increase in aberration risk (OR=1.039, 95% CI 1.013–1.067). </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Biologically, these findings are consistent with ionizing radiation generating DNA double-strand breaks either directly or via free radicals from water radiolysis; imperfect repair through non-homologous end joining or homologous recombination can yield structural chromosome changes.  Age-related declines in repair capacity may further increase susceptibility to accumulated damage, providing a plausible mechanistic link between aging, longer service, and higher CA prevalence. </p></div></section><section class="content-section section-gray" data-v-8856cefa><h2 class="section-title" data-v-8856cefa>Conclusion</h2><div class="section-content" data-v-8856cefa><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> This occupational health study provides institution-level evidence that long-term, low-dose ionizing radiation exposure in medical radiation diagnostics practice is associated with an increased prevalence of chromosomal aberrations in peripheral blood immune cells. Using standardized cytogenetic scoring criteria and routine occupational medical examination data from 1,125 workers assessed during 2023–2024, the study identified a measurable aberration burden in a minority of practitioners (5.8%), with affected individuals tending to be older and to have longer exposure duration than their non-aberrant peers.  </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> Critically, multivariate logistic regression showed that cumulative exposure duration remained an independent risk factor after adjustment for gender and blood indices: each additional year of occupational radiation exposure increased the odds of chromosomal aberrations by approximately 3.9% (OR=1.039, 95% CI 1.013–1.067).  This quantitative association supports the interpretation that chronic exposure contributes to accumulated DNA damage and misrepair, consistent with the mechanistic framework in which double-strand breaks and imperfect repair pathways generate dicentrics, rings, and fragments. </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> From a practical perspective, the findings argue for strengthening occupational health surveillance and radiation protection measures for medical radiation practitioners, with particular attention to workers with long service histories. The article specifically recommends reinforcing monitoring systems, improving protective equipment through customization and intelligent upgrades, and promoting remote/automated operational technologies to reduce exposure opportunities.  For higher-risk groups, shortening monitoring intervals and implementing supportive interventions were proposed as additional strategies. </p><p class="section-text" data-v-8856cefa> While the study is informative for workplace management, it is based on examinations from a single tertiary hospital and focuses on exposure duration rather than individual dosimetry records. Future multi-center studies that integrate badge dose histories, task-specific exposure profiles, and longitudinal follow-up would help refine risk stratification and evaluate the impact of targeted protection policies over time. </p></div></section>',4)])])}],["__scopeId","data-v-8856cefa"]]);export{o as default};
